:INFO
The Most Beautifully Written Book With the Worst Narrator
Lolita requires you to hold two things at the same time: the extraordinary beauty \
of Nabokov's prose and the complete moral failure of the person producing it. \
Humbert Humbert is a pedophile who presents himself as a lover and uses the \
language of literature to construct a case for his own victimhood. The novel \
is the most complete demonstration I know of the idea that beautiful language \
can be in the service of something monstrous, and reading it is a lesson in \
how literature can implicate you.

:NOTE
The beauty of the prose is the trap. Nabokov intended it and it works.

:QUOTE [subtitle:Vladimir Nabokov, quotetype:PLAIN]
Lolita, light of my life, fire of my loins.

:JOURNEY
Reading Lolita
Section
Impact
- The opening | 4 | Implicating prose | Beautiful and draws you into Humbert's frame
- Road trip chapters | 3 | Numbing by design | Humbert's normalizing voice does its work
- Quilty sections | 4 | Curtain lifted | Where the novel reveals what it has been doing
- The ending | 5 | Reality breaks through | The only moment Nabokov allows the truth in

:NOTE
The novel is frequently discussed as primarily a linguistic achievement. It is also \
a precise account of abuse framed to seem like love, and reading it critically \
requires keeping that distinction in view throughout.

:POLL
Do you think Lolita is a masterpiece, a problematic book, or both?
A masterpiece precisely because of the discomfort it creates
Both, and the tension between them is what makes it last
Problematic in ways that outweigh its literary achievement
I have not read it and am uncertain whether I want to
